- type: disease
- source: MONDO
- details:
  - mondo_name: perinatal necrotizing enterocolitis
  - mondo_definition: A fulminating disease of neonates in which there is extensive mucosal ulceration, pseudomembrane formation, submucosal hemorrhage, and necrosis usually of the right colon, cecum, terminal ileum, and appendix, possibly due to perinatal intestinal ischemia and bacterial invasion. Progression can lead to necrosis, perforation and/or scarring of the intestinal tract.
  - umls_description: Inflammation of the colon that is caused by an alteration in intestinal flora by antibiotic use.

- - name: constitutional neutropenia
- type: disease
- source: MONDO
- details:
  - mondo_name: constitutional neutropenia
  - mondo_definition: A rare disorder characterized by recurrent infantile infections and absence of neutrophils in the peripheral blood.
  - umls_description: A decrease in the number of granulocytes;

- - name: severe congenital neutropenia
- type: disease
- source: MONDO_grouped
- details:
  - mondo_name: autosomal dominant severe congenital neutropenia
  - group_name_bert: severe congenital neutropenia
  - mondo_definition: Autosomal dominant form of severe congenital neutropenia.
  - umls_description: A decrease in the number of granulocytes;
  - orphanet_definition: A rare primary immunodeficiency disorder characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, absolute neutrophil counts below 0.5x10E9/L in the peripheral blood (on three separate occasions over a six month period), granulopoiesis maturation arrest at the promyelocyte/myelocyte stage and early-onset, severe, recurrent bacterial infections.
  - orphanet_prevalence: <1/1000000

- - name: X-linked severe congenital neutropenia
- type: disease
- source: MONDO
- details:
  - mondo_name: X-linked severe congenital neutropenia
  - mondo_definition: This syndrome is an immunodeficiency syndrome characterized by recurrent major bacterial infections, severe congenital neutropenia, and monocytopenia. It has been described in five males spanning three generations of one family. It is transmitted as an X-linked recessive trait and is caused by mutations in the WAS gene, encoding the WASP protein.
  - umls_description: A decrease in the number of granulocytes;
